cisions on sound evidence for what will create the best possible policies, and to promote the common good rather than their own self-interest. They must vote well--or not vote at all. Brennan explains why voting is not necessarily the best way for citizens to exercise their civic duty, and why some citizens need to stay away from the polls to protect the democratic process from their uninformed, irrational, or immoral votes. In a democracy, every citizen has the right to vote. This book reveals why sometimes it's best if they don't. In a new afterword, "How to Vote Well," Brennan provides a practical guidebook for making well-informed, well-reasoned choices at the polls.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aVotingxMoral and ethical aspects. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / General.2bisacsh  aAgency Argument.  aCivic Virtue Argument.  aPublic Goods Argument.  aabstention.  aautonomy.  abad governance.  abad voting.  abeneficial policies.  acausal responsibility.  acitizens.  acivic duty.  acivic virtue.  acommon good.  acommunity volunteering.  acontemporary liberal democracies.  adeference.  ademocracy.  aegoistic voting.  aepistemic justification.  aepistemic standards.  aextrapolitical conception.  afortuitous voting.  agood governance.  agood intentions.  agood policy.  agood voting.  agovernment policies.  agovernment.  aharmful policies.  aharmful voting.  aindependent judgment.  ainformed decisions.  amilitary service.  amoral obligation.  amoral obligations.  amoral virtue.  anational interest.  anews.  apersonal biases.  apolitical beliefs.  apolitical judgment.  apolitical movements.  apolitical participation.  apolitical parties.  apolitics.  apublic-spirited voting.  aself-interest.  asocial order.  asoci